First Call for Papers

SEPLN 2005
XXI CONGRESO DE LA SOCIEDAD ESPA=D1OLA PARA EL PROCESAMIENTO DEL LENGUAJE=20
NATURAL (SEPLN)
(21th Conference of the Spanish Society for Natural Language Processing =AD=
=20
SEPLN)

September 14-16, 2005
Palacio de Exposiciones y Congresos
Granada (Spain)


Introduction

The 21th Conference of the Spanish Society for Natural Language Processing=
=20
(SEPLN) will take place on September 14-16, 2005 in Granada (Spain). As in=
=20
previous editions, the aim of SEPLN for this Conference is to promote the=20
dissemination of research, development and innovation activities conducted=
=20
by Spanish and foreign researchers in the field of Natural Language=20
Processing (NLP). The conference will provide a forum for discussion and=20
communication to facilitate an effective exchange of knowledge and=20
scientific materials that are necessary for promoting the publication of=20
relevant work and the establishment of means of collaboration with national=
=20
and international Institutions that are active in this field.

Objectives

The main motivation of this conference is to provide the business and=20
scientific communities with an ideal forum for presenting their latest=20
research work and developments in the field of Natural Language Processing,=
=20
as well as to demonstrate the possibilities offered by these solutions and=
=20
to know about new projects. Consequently, the 21th SEPLN Conference is a=20
meeting place for presenting results and exchanging ideas concerning the=20
present state of development in this field of knowledge.

Furthermore, there is the intention of meeting the goal, achieved in=20
previous editions, of identifying future paths for basic research and=20
foreseen software applications, in order to compare them against the market=
=20
needs. Finally, the conference intends to be an appropriate forum in=20
helping new professionals to become active members in this field.

Topics

Researchers and businesses are encouraged to send communications, project=20
abstracts or demonstrations related to any of the following topics:

    * Linguistic, mathematic and psycholinguistic models of language
    * Corpus linguistics
    * Monolingual and multilingual information extraction and retrieval
    * Formalisms and grammars for morphological and syntactical analysis
    * Computational Lexicography
    * Monolingual and multilingual text generation
    * Machine translation
    * Speech synthesis and recognition
    * Semantics, pragmatics and discourse
    * Word sense disambiguation
    * NLP industrial applications
    * Automatic textual content analysis


Structure of the Conference

The Conference will last three days, with sessions dedicated to presenting=
=20
papers, ongoing research projects, prototype product demonstrations or=20
products connected with topics addressed in the conference. Scientific=20
activities will be complemented by social and tourist activities, allowing=
=20
attendants to gain a better understanding about the social and cultural=20
dimensions of Granada.

Communications

Authors are encouraged to send theoretical or system-related proposals, to=
=20
be presented at the demonstration sessions, earlier than <deadline>April 22, 2005</deadline>.=20
Proposals must meet certain format and style requirements

Both the delivery and revision of proposals will be done exclusively in=20
electronic format (PostScript or PDF). Proposals will include a title, the=
=20
complete names of the authors, their address, telephone, fax and e-mail.

Proposals will meet the following requirements (concerning the final=20
version, please check the =93publication format=94 section):

    * The proposals will be presented in Spanish or English.
    * Inclusion of an abstract (maximum 150 words).
    * Related topic.
    * Overall maximum length will be 3,500 words (including the abstract).
    * The proposals will be anonymously revised. Therefore, two separate=20
files will be submitted, one will only include the title and author=20
details, the other will only include the title and the rest of the proposal.
    * Final versions (after notification of acceptance) will follow the=20
style requirements that are described in the publication format section.

Authors will submit their proposals through a web system that will be=20
communicated in the Second Call for Papers.


Projects and Demos

As in previous editions, the organizers encourage participants to give oral=
=20
presentations of projects and demos. Depending on the estimated number of=20
oral presentations, any session may be reserved to this purpose. Proposals=
=20
must meet certain format and style requirements for presentations.

For oral presentation of projects to be accepted, the following information=
=20
must be included:
    * Project title
    * Funding institution
    * Participant groups in the project
    * Name, affiliation, e-mail and phone number of the project director
    * Abstract (2 pages maximum)
    * If a demonstration is to be performed, further information must be=20
included, as indicated below

For demonstrations to be accepted, the following information is mandatory:
    * Name, affiliation, e-mail and phone number of the authors
    * Abstract (2 pages maximum)
    * Time estimation for the whole presentation

This information must be received by <deadline>May 20, 2005</deadline>.


Publication Format

The final version of the article will be sent before <deadline>June 3, 2005</deadline> through=20
the same web system.
    * Documents must not include headers or footings.
    * Maximum length will be 8 pages DIN A4 (210 x 297 mm), included=20
references and figures.
    * In the case of demonstrations and projects, maximum length will be 2=
=20
pages.

Articles will be sent in Postscript or PDF format.


LaTeX format

Authors using LaTeX format will download from the Conference website (URL=20
to be communicated in the Second Call for Papers) the following style=20
package zip file: latex_new.zip which will contain document and=20
bibliography styles, as well as an example showing existing editing=20
possibilities.


Word format

Authors using Microsoft Word or compatible will download from the=20
Conference website the following zip file: word_new.zip which will include=
=20
a pattern file in RTF format and an example showing existing editing=20
possibilities.


Important Dates

Dates for submission and notifications of acceptance:

- Deadline for submitting abstracts: <deadline>April 22, 2005</deadline>
- Notification of acceptance: May 24, 2005
- Deadline for submitting the final version: <deadline>June 3, 2005</deadline>
- Deadline for submitting projects and demos: <deadline>May 20, 2005</deadline>


